Hong Kong &mdash; Asian shares slipped for a second day as energy shares paced declines on lower oil prices, offsetting gains in property stocks.The MSCI Asia Pacific Index slid 0.2% as of 10:35am in Hong Kong following a 0.2% drop on Tuesday. Oil fell for a third day as industry data showed US crude stockpiles rose. Investors are also sifting through earnings reports and awaiting further signals from the new US administration."The market is likely to move sideways until there is more clarity on Trump policies," said Alan Richardson, a Hong Kong-based investment manager at Samsung Asset Management. "Oil&rsquo;s upside is capped by supply risks, and it&rsquo;s unlikely to see strong earnings in the energy sector."The MSCI Asia Pacific energy index declined 0.8%. JX Holdings slumped 2.7% in Tokyo, while PetroChina dropped 1.7% in Hong Kong.The MSCI Asia Pacific real estate index rose 0.4% as analysts at Goldman Sachs Group and Citigroup said China&rsquo;s property developers were in far better shape than their rock-bottom stock valuations indicated.The Topix index was down 0.1%, while the Shanghai composite index dropped 0.4%. The Hang Seng Index fell 0.5%. The S&amp;P/ASX 200 rose 0.3%, while South Korea&rsquo;s Kospi slipped 1%.Bloomberg